                        "type": "0",
                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "<p>During the termination phase of the nurse-client relationship, the clinic nurse observes that the client has made several sarcastic remarks and has an angry affect. Which is the most appropriate interpretation of the client's behavior?</p>",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "<p>Rationale:</p><p>In the termination phase of a relationship, it is normal for a client to demonstrate a number of regressive behaviors that can be disturbing to the nurse. Typical behaviors include return of symptoms, anger, withdrawal, and minimizing the relationship. The anger that the client is experiencing is a normal feeling during the termination phase and does not necessarily indicate the need for hospitalization or treatment.</p><p><br></p><p>Client Needs: Psychosocial Integrity</p><p>Clinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Analyze Cues</p><p>Cognitive Ability: Analyzing</p><p>Content Area: Mental Health</p><p>Integrated Process: Nursing Process/Analysis</p><p>Priority Concepts: Mood and Affect, Communication</p><p>Strategies: Comparable or Alike Options, Strategic Words, Subject</p><p><br></p><p>Test-Taking Strategy:</p><p>Note the strategic words, most appropriate. Focus on the subject, client behaviors during the termination phase. Additionally, note that the incorrect options are comparable or alike; they all address the need for further supervised treatment.</p>",
                        "id": "7c4b725696c64355aac8570ae71103ce",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
